<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Fisher &amp; Paykel is New Zealand's luxury brand — we see them in Venice, Silver Lake, and Malibu kitchens where owners wanted European-quality design without the European price tag.</h2>

    <p>Fisher &amp; Paykel Appliances (Auckland, New Zealand, founded 1934, owned by Haier Group since 2012) occupies a specific position in the LA luxury appliance market. F&amp;P offers the design language and engineering quality of Miele or Bosch — minimalist controls, integrated panel-ready aesthetics, build quality that ages well — at a price point that runs roughly 20-30% below the European brands on directly comparable categories. The result is a brand that gets specified into custom kitchens by owners who care about how the appliances look and feel but who balked at full Miele or Sub-Zero pricing across an entire suite. Venice and Silver Lake mid-century renovations, Mar Vista contemporary builds, Malibu canyon properties, and Pacific Palisades remodels are the recurring F&amp;P installation patterns we see on our route.</p>

    <p>Three F&amp;P-specific realities shape every service call we run. First, <strong>the DishDrawer is the brand's signature differentiator and a genuinely different appliance from any standard dishwasher</strong>. F&amp;P invented the drawer-format dishwasher in 1997; the DD60 double configuration is two independent washing chambers stacked vertically, each with its own water inlet, drain, wash motor, control board, and seal system. Service tree on a DishDrawer has almost nothing in common with a Miele G-series or Bosch 800-series standard machine — different mechanism, different failure ordering, different parts catalog. The 2016-2021 DD60 latch mechanism wears predictably around year 5-6, and that pattern alone accounts for a meaningful share of our LA F&amp;P volume. Second, <strong>F&amp;P parts route through Haier's US distribution since the 2012 acquisition</strong> — meaning the same logistics infrastructure that supports GE Appliances (Haier acquired GE Appliances in 2016) now supports F&amp;P parts availability. Lead times have improved significantly compared to the pre-2012 era when F&amp;P parts came directly from New Zealand. Third, <strong>ActiveSmart adaptive refrigeration on the RF-series is a different diagnostic path than a standard thermostat fault</strong>. ActiveSmart is the brand's adaptive-learning system that tracks usage patterns and adjusts cooling cycles; when it fails the unit presents as inconsistent temperatures rather than a clean on/off thermostat symptom, and the service work is on the control board rather than a temperature sensor.</p>

    <p>This page covers F&amp;P repair across the full US lineup. Every F&amp;P service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM Fisher &amp; Paykel parts via the Haier US distribution network, and an honest written quote with parts lead-time disclosed before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 DISHDRAWER -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, DishDrawer — the F&amp;P signature category</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">DD60 double and DD24 single DishDrawer service is genuinely different from standard dishwasher repair.</h2>

    <p class="lead">DishDrawer is a patented F&amp;P invention — the drawer-format dishwasher introduced in 1997 and refined across multiple production generations since. Each drawer is an independent washing appliance: independent water inlet, drain pump, wash motor, control board, and door-seal system. Double DD60 configurations stack two of these as parallel-operating units, so you can run a delicate-glassware cycle in the top drawer while the bottom runs a heavy pots-and-pans cycle simultaneously. Venice and Silver Lake open-plan kitchens love the format because the drawer aesthetic fits the minimalist millwork — the dishwasher disappears into the cabinetry rather than dominating with a full-height door.</p>

    <div class="callout-box">
      <h3>2016-2021 DD60 latch mechanism pattern (most common F&amp;P service call in LA)</h3>
      <p>The DD60DCHTX9 and surrounding DD60 production years between roughly 2016 and 2021 develop a consistent drawer latch mechanism failure around year 5 to 6. Symptoms: drawer won't latch closed, cycle won't start, sometimes a partial latch that triggers cycle start then aborts mid-wash. <strong>Left drawer fails first</strong> in most double configurations — left-drawer use is heavier across LA installations because of how kitchen counter-flow patterns work (loading dirty dishes from the left, transferring clean dishes to drying rack or cabinets on the right). Right drawer typically follows 12-18 months later on the same wear curve. Replacement runs $245-$385 per drawer; we often stock the common DD60 latch on the truck for same-day completion. Worth diagnosing both drawers when one fails — if the right drawer is at year 4-5 it's heading the same direction and a preventive paired-service visit saves a second dispatch.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond the latch pattern, DishDrawer service covers a predictable component tree:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 4-6:</strong> Drawer seal compression and wear ($185-$285) — the silicone seal that closes the drawer against the cabinet face hardens and loses compression. Leaking or steam escape during cycle is the symptom.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5-6:</strong> Drawer latch mechanism (above) — the dominant DD60 service item.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 6-8:</strong> Water inlet solenoid valve ($185-$285) — drawer-specific valve, different part than a standard dishwasher inlet. Hard water in LA accelerates this on unfiltered installs.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 7-9:</strong> Wash motor ($345-$525) — the drawer's circulation motor. Reduced wash quality (poorly cleaned dishes, especially top drawer with delicate glassware) is the symptom.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 7-10:</strong> Drain pump ($245-$385).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8-10:</strong> Drawer control board ($345-$525) — each drawer has its own. Failure isolation matters: on a double DD60 one drawer can need a new board while the other runs perfectly.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Our techs know which subsystem belongs to which drawer — important on double DD60 service where the customer's experience is "the bottom drawer isn't working" but the diagnostic needs to isolate which specific component within that drawer is failing without touching the top drawer's parallel hardware. Same-day completion is realistic on the common items (latch, seal, inlet valve) when we have the part on the truck.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 REFRIGERATORS & ACTIVESMART -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Refrigerators — RF-series and ActiveSmart</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">F&amp;P French door fridges and integrated columns share the ActiveSmart adaptive platform.</h2>

    <p class="lead">The RF-series refrigerators (RF170WLHK1, RF201, RF522 the dominant US configurations) plus the F&amp;P integrated panel-ready columns sit at the second-largest service category in our F&amp;P mix. The defining technical feature is ActiveSmart — F&amp;P's adaptive-learning refrigeration system that monitors door-open patterns, ambient temperature swings, and cooling-demand cycles to adjust compressor and fan operation in near-real-time. When it works, ActiveSmart produces noticeably more stable internal temperatures and lower energy consumption than fixed-cycle refrigeration. When it fails, the diagnostic path is different from a standard refrigerator.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>ActiveSmart control board (vs simple thermostat)</h3>
        <p>When ActiveSmart fails the unit doesn't present as "thermostat broken." It presents as inconsistent temperatures across compartments, periodic over-cooling, or the freezer running differently than the fresh-food side. Diagnostic is on the ActiveSmart main control board ($385-$585), not on a temperature sensor. Common at year 8-12. Different parts ecosystem than standard fridge repair — our techs identify the ActiveSmart pattern at diagnostic.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>RF-series evaporator fan motor</h3>
        <p>Year 7-9 typical. Symptom: warm spots in the fresh-food compartment (top usually first), freezer still cold. Reduced airflow over the evaporator is the root cause. $245-$385 replacement. Common on RF170 and RF201 — the larger French door configurations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Ice maker assembly</h3>
        <p>$345-$525. The integrated ice maker in the freezer compartment. Failure modes: not producing, small/hollow cubes, leaking. Hard-water mineral buildup is the most common LA accelerant. We test water quality at diagnostic when ice symptoms come in.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Integrated column refrigerators</h3>
        <p>F&amp;P's panel-ready integrated columns (the RS series) compete in the Sub-Zero column category at a meaningfully lower price point. Service tree overlaps the RF-series on ActiveSmart and evaporator fan, but the integrated installation adds cabinet-fit and panel-alignment service items on its own. More common in custom kitchens than the freestanding French doors.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Door gasket and seal</h3>
        <p>$185-$285. Year 5-7 typical. Damaged or compressed gaskets let warm air infiltrate — the unit compensates by running the compressor longer (higher energy use, accelerated component wear). Often paired with a hinge alignment service if the door geometry has shifted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Compressor / sealed system</h3>
        <p>$680-$980. Year 12-15 typical. At this point we walk you through repair-vs-replace math, though F&amp;P replacement-unit pricing ($3,500-$5,500 for RF-series) keeps the calculation on the repair side more reliably than it does on entry-tier brands.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 LAUNDRY, COOKING, OUTDOOR -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Laundry, cooking, range hoods</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">WH washers, DE dryers, OR ranges, OB wall ovens, HC range hoods.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Beyond DishDrawer and refrigerator, F&amp;P's US lineup covers the full kitchen and laundry suite. Each category has its own service profile but the underlying engineering quality (and the repair-vs-replace math) is consistent across the lineup.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>WH-series washers (front-load)</h3>
        <p>WH1060P2 is the dominant model in our LA service mix. Service tree: drain pump year 5-7 ($245-$385), door boot gasket year 6-8 ($185-$285), drum bearing year 7-10 ($585-$885 — larger tub-out service), control board year 8-10 ($345-$525). Marine-climate New Zealand engineering produces good corrosion resistance on coastal LA addresses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>DE-series dryers (condenser / heat pump)</h3>
        <p>DE6060P2 is the matching condenser/heat-pump dryer to the WH washer line. Service tree: heating element year 6-8 ($185-$285), condenser unit year 7-9 ($385-$585 on heat-pump variants), control board year 8-10, drum belt year 6-8. Heat-pump variants are more complex but more energy-efficient — service skews toward the heat exchanger on those.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>OR-series ranges (induction / dual-fuel / gas)</h3>
        <p>OR90SDMBGX2 and the OR series — 30, 36, 48-inch ranges with induction, dual-fuel, and gas variants. Induction generator board on induction OR variants ($485-$685, year 7-10); gas igniter / spark module on gas variants ($185-$285, year 4-6); oven door hinge ($185-$285); convection fan motor ($285-$425); temperature probe ($185-$285).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>OB-series wall ovens, CI/CG cooktops</h3>
        <p>The OB60 induction-platform integrated cooking system and the standalone CI induction and CG gas cooktops. Service items: induction generator board, glass-top crack replacement on induction variants ($485-$685), gas burner valve ($185-$285), control panel and bezel.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>HC-series range hoods</h3>
        <p>Wall-mount and island configurations. Service items: blower motor ($285-$425), control panel, lighting circuit, baffle filters. Lower service volume than the DishDrawer and refrigerator sides but recurring.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Haier family parts ecosystem</h3>
        <p>F&amp;P parts route through Haier's US distribution since 2012. Haier also owns GE Appliances (acquired 2016) — same parent, shared logistics. Practical service implication: F&amp;P parts availability in LA is significantly better than the pre-2012 era when parts came directly from New Zealand. Typical 5-10 day lead on less-common items; common DD60 / RF / WH wear parts on the truck.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 PRICING -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Pricing</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What Fisher &amp; Paykel appliance repair costs in Southern California.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when you approve the work. F&amp;P pricing sits in the mid-luxury repair tier — parts ship from Haier's US distribution (F&amp;P parent since 2012), typical 5-10 day lead for less-common items, common wear parts for the dominant DD60 / RF / WH / DE series on the truck for same-day completion.</p>

    <div class="pricing-grid">
      <div class="price-card">
        <div class="price-label">Diagnostic</div>
        <div class="price-amount">$89</div>
        <div class="price-desc">Waived when you approve repair</div>
      </div>
      <div class="price-card">
        <div class="price-label">Standard band</div>
        <div class="price-amount">$185–$385</div>
        <div class="price-desc">DishDrawer latch · drain pump · door gasket · igniter · thermostat · heating element</div>
      </div>
      <div class="price-card">
        <div class="price-label">Major component</div>
        <div class="price-amount">$345–$585</div>
        <div class="price-desc">Wash motor · ActiveSmart control board · evaporator fan · convection fan · induction generator</div>
      </div>
      <div class="price-card">
        <div class="price-label">Compressor / drum bearing</div>
        <div class="price-amount">$585–$980</div>
        <div class="price-desc">Out-of-warranty compressor swap · washer drum bearing (tub-out service) · sealed-system work</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="price-note">Repair-vs-replace math on Fisher &amp; Paykel almost always lands on the repair side. Replacement-unit pricing is $2,000-$5,000 per appliance (DD60 DishDrawer around $2,800, RF170 French door fridge around $4,500, WH1060 washer around $1,800, OR90 induction range around $5,500). A $385 DishDrawer latch on a 6-year-old DD60 ($2,800 replacement) is obvious math; even a $980 compressor swap on an RF170 at year 12 ($4,500 replacement) keeps repair on the right side of the calculation. The F&amp;P repair-vs-replace conversation is shorter than it is on most brands because the math is so consistently on the repair side — we tell you the numbers at diagnostic but the recommendation is rarely "replace."</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Fisher &amp; Paykel jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Three representative service calls — model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; technical scenarios are typical of what we see on F&amp;P service.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>F&amp;P DD60DCHTX9 double DishDrawer, Silver Lake</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Bottom drawer wouldn't latch closed — owner could push the drawer in but the latch wouldn't engage, so the cycle never started. Top drawer worked normally. Had been intermittent for 2 weeks, fully failed 3 days before the call. Unit was 6 years old, mid-century kitchen renovation.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Classic 2016-2021 DD60 latch mechanism failure on the heavier-use drawer. Latch tested showed worn pawl geometry — the engagement surface had developed enough wear that the cam couldn't reliably catch. Top drawer latch inspected and showed early wear signs but still within service spec (estimated 12-18 months of remaining life on its current trajectory).</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Bottom drawer latch mechanism replacement with OEM F&amp;P part (in stock on truck). Verified clean latch engagement and complete cycle start on test wash. Customer authorized preventive top-drawer latch replacement on the same visit to avoid a second dispatch when the matching wear-out arrives.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $545 total (two drawer latches — paired preventive service). Same-day, 90 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>F&amp;P RF170WLHK1 French door refrigerator, Venice</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Fresh-food compartment running inconsistent — owner reported milk going off faster than usual and lettuce wilting within 3-4 days. Freezer side seemed fine. No obvious door-seal damage. Unit was 9 years old, open-plan kitchen.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> ActiveSmart control board partial failure — the adaptive cycling had stopped tracking door-open patterns and was running stuck in default fixed-cycle mode. The result was over-cooling cycles followed by drift-warm periods that average out to "looks roughly normal on the display" but produces the inconsistent food preservation the customer described. Temperature data logger placed in fresh-food compartment over the diagnostic window confirmed the pattern.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> ActiveSmart main control board replacement with OEM F&amp;P part. Verified adaptive cycling re-engaged and temperatures stabilized over a 12-hour soak test before close-out. Door gasket inspected and found acceptable for the unit's age.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $485 total. Same-day, 2 hours on-site (control board on truck for the RF-series).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>F&amp;P WH1060P2 front-load washer, Malibu</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Loud knocking on spin cycle, getting progressively worse over about 3 weeks. Owner noticed brown water residue on a few light-colored loads — consistent with bearing-failure rust contamination. Unit was 8 years old, beach-adjacent property.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Drum bearing failure — year 8 on the WH-series, within expected service curve. Bearing wear had progressed enough that the drum was wobbling on spin and contaminating wash water with bearing-race material. Tub seal also degraded (predictable — bearing and seal fail together). Coastal salt-air corrosion on terminal connections was minor for an 8-year beach property, manageable.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Drum bearing assembly replacement with OEM F&amp;P parts — tub-out service, the larger F&amp;P washer repair. Replaced bearing, tub seal, and drum-side gasket as a paired kit (standard service practice — never reuse the seal when the bearing's been replaced). Tested across short, normal, and heavy-load cycles before close-out.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $785 total (tub-out bearing service). Same-day, 4 hours on-site.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 07 SERVICE AREAS -->
<section class="section">
